Nelson Sullivan (1948-1989) was a video artist who documented downtown New York City in the 1980s. Originally from South Carolina, Sullivan moved to Manhattan in the 1970s and began filming the city's art world and gay scene. He captured John Sex, Sylvia Miles, RuPaul, and other performers at downtown bars and nightclubs including Danceteria, the Limelight, Palladium, and the Pyramid Club. Sullivan also chronicled house parties at his apartment at 5 Ninth Avenue in the Meatpacking District, gallery openings, park and street festivals, conversations with taxi drivers, and the ruminations of his friends including fashion designer Alexis Del Lago and journalist Michael Musto on film. He recorded almost 2,000 hours of tape, at first using a VHS-loading camera and later an 8mm video camera. Sullivan's filmmaking is recognizable for its point of view transitions and its stream-of-consciousness narration. He also often pointed a wide-angle lens at his own face while filming to record his commentary on the people, performances, or events that he captured. Sullivan made films up until his death from a heart attack on July 4, 1989.

unittitle.value: Now Explosion at the Pyramid Club

p.value: Part one of this video from November 16, 1983, shows Nelson spending time in the Pyramid Club dressing room prior to a performance by the Atlanta, Georgia, band The Now Explosion. Among those in the video are Deloris French, John Sex, and members of The Now Explosion.

Part two of this video is a continuation of The Now Explosion performing at the Pyramid Club. After their performance, there is a dance contest with Doctor Tony and Joan Ransom from the PTA, then footage from the Pyramid Club dressing room after the show. Finally, there is footage of a party Nelson attends in "Bobby and John's" apartment.

The first disc of this video starts with footage from the morning of November 20, 1983, when the Chelsea Hotel lobby is being prepared for a party. Nelson goes to room 604 to spend time with friends, including Sandy Dancer, Michael Musto, and Deloris French. Sandy Dancer prepares for her performance later in the day. When a news camera crew interviews Sandy, she says that the party is a birthday celebration for the Chelsea.

The second disc begins with people flowing in and out of room 604 while Sandy Dancer finishes preparing for her performance. There is a dance performance in the stairwell before the main party in the lobby, where, among others, Sandy Dancer and Michael Musto perform. Ed Koch appears after a couple songs in order to honor the Chelsea Hotel on its 100th anniversary and declare November 20, 1983 Chelsea Hotel Day. Koch also presents playwright Arthur Miller with a plaque honoring his time living at the Chelsea. Miller gives brief remarks before the unveiling of his plaque. Ulick O'Connor speaks on behalf of the history of the Chelsea, and there are a couple more performances.
Current DVD is damaged and skips from around 56 minutes to 58 minutes.

This video documents performances and a party in the Chelsea Hotel lobby on November 20, 1983. Towards the end of the night, someone in the hotel accidentally pulls a fire alarm and everyone moves outside temporarily. Among those featured are Sandy Dancer, Sylvia Miles, and Cookie Mueller.

On June 13, 1986, Nelson films a performance by Joshua at Darinka. The Because Family Picnic (John, Dina, and Joshua) performs in between two sets by Joshua. For a short amount of time, Nelson goes backstage and speaks with the performers. The video ends with Nelson walking alone down the street.

The video starts with Nelson and friends driving to Pizza-a-Go-Go for White Trash Night on October 10, 1984. When they arrive, Nelson wanders around the building before Michael Musto and the Must's performance starts. He bumps into Musto in the dressing room getting ready and warming up. Then, Michael Musto and the Must perform covers of popular songs by girl groups. After the show, Nelson goes backstage with the musicians and others for a while before going to the kitchen, where a Beatles cover band is performing. Then, Nelson and friends drive around and end up in a cafe.

Nelson and his friends get dinner near the Chelsea Hotel before heading to Limelight for a show on April 1, 1986. When they arrive at Limelight, Nelson records the performers getting ready to perform in the dressing room. Then he moves to the dancefloor to record the audience before Tabboo!'s puppet show. After that ends, Shazork (Lady Bunny, DJ Dmitri Brill, and Sister Dimension's band) takes the stage. After the show, Nelson heads back stage briefly before leaving Limelight and heading to the a restaurant, where the video ends.

unittitle.value: Atlanta: RuPaul at Weekends and Larry Tee's Celebrity Club

p.value: The video starts with RuPaul gogo dancing at the Atlanta nightclub Weekends on February 27, 1986, then Nelson goes into RuPaul's private dressing room with Larry Tee and a couple of others. When RuPaul finishes his set, he joins the group. The video jumps to the next day, with Nelson spending time in a friend's house. His friend then gives him a tour on a drive through Atlanta on their way to lunch at Burton's Grill. The tour continues before they return to the house where Larry Tee and others have gathered to watch some recorded performances. Larry Tee then takes Nelson on a drive to what will become Larry Tee's Celebrity Club for a tour, which is still under construction. The video jumps again, to Nelson chatting with drag queens (Sultra, Wanda, and others) getting ready for the night and then doing a private performance/interview for Nelson. Finally, the video jumps to recordings of music videos by Spencer Thorton for The Now Explosion, RuPaul, and an unknown band. The video cuts off at the beginning of a clip titled "RuPaul, Tune-Up King."

On October 12, 1984, Nelson attended RuPaul's performance in Danceteria. The video starts with a group getting ready in RuPaul's dressing room, then shows all of the performance, featuring special guest Miss Felicia. After the show, Nelson goes backstage to congratulate RuPaul and Felicia on the show, and he spends the rest of the recording the group hanging out there.

unittitle.value: Louise Nevelson in Conversation at the Guggenheim

p.value: Nelson and Sylvia Miles attend a dialogue between sculptor Louise Nevelson and critic and editor of New Criterion Hilton Kramer at the Guggenheim in this video, dated March 5, 1986. The conversation is in celebration of Nevelson's being awarded The Great Artist Series Award by New York University's Gallatin Division, for her contribution to international art and culture. After the talk, Nelson and Sylvia go to the reception in the Guggenheim's rotunda, where they speak with Louise.

Nelson records performers getting ready for the March 15, 1986 show of Ethyl Eichelberger's campy comedy Casanova at the Performing Garage, starring Eichelberger, Lady Bunny, Lola Pashalinski, Katy Dierlam, and Barbara Wise. Nelson briefly goes backstage after the performance, where among the crowds, Sylvia Miles and Peter Hujar are present.

Disc one of this video starts with Nelson receiving a phone call from Liz to make plans on March 15, 1986. Then Nelson spends time with his dog, Blackout, and his cats, Freddie and Eddie, telling them that it's his birthday. He takes Blackout for a short walk before heading to 7A Cafe to meet his friends, including Michael Musto. Nelson, Michael, and Liz then travel to Musto's family home.

In disc two, Nelson, Michael, and Liz finally arrive at the Musto's family home in Bensonhurst and chat with Michael's family. They then drive to Albert's new house, receive a tour, and eat dinner. Nelson, Michael, and Liz leave Albert's apartment, and the video ends with them in the car.

unittitle.value: The Now Explosion at the Pyramid Club

p.value: Disc one shows The Now Explosion performing at The Pyramid Club. Towards the end of their performance, they're joined on stage by RuPaul. After the show, Nelson goes backstage to spend time with the band.

Disc two is a continuation of The Now Explosion's performance at The Pyramid Club on the same night. After a short break, they take the stage again, and RuPaul once again joins them for a few songs. Lady Bunny also joins them onstage for a couple songs.

Nelson is backstage with Buster Poindexter and the other musicians while they warm up before their show at Limelight on November 19, 1985, then heads out to the audience. The show is celebrating Buster Poindexter's birthday. Susan Kirschner joins Buster on stage for several songs. Afterwards, Nelson goes backstage again briefly.
On August 29 and 30, 1984, Nelson records his stay in Provincetown. Nelson and Sylvia Miles explore Provincetown together, bumping into friends wherever they go.
On August 27 and 28, 1984, Nelson records his stay in Provincetown. The video features Nelson, Sylvia Miles, Bob Haas, and others exploring the town at a leisurely pace.
On disc one, Nelson and Sylvia Miles attend Michael Musto's birthday party at Amsterdam's restaurant with many others on December 18, 1985. The video ends with a group going outside to hail a cab.
On disc two, more people arrive at the party, including a singing stripper, Jon St. John, and Andy Warhol. Nelson and friends leave the party and take a cab.

unittitle.value: Beyond the Valley of La Cage at Limelight

p.value: This video documents the December 17, 1985 drag show at Limelight, Beyond the Valley of La Cage. Nelson goes backstage and shows some of the performers getting ready for the night. Then he films the performance, which features drag queens impersonating their favorite pop stars. After the show, Nelson goes backstage to spend time with the performers.
Nelson is backstage at the Pyramid Club with Shazork as they get ready to perform on May 12, 1986. He then films their short teaser performance, before filming their later full performance.

unittitle.value: David Chicklet's Birthday Party, Shazork at Danceteria, and Shazork at the Pyramid Club

p.value: This video opens with David Chicklet's tenth birthday party at Limelight on December 6, 1985, where Michael Musto and others make an appearance. After that, Nelson heads to Danceteria for Shazork's performance. The video also shows footage from December 15 at the Pyramid Club, for a show by an unidentified band, then Shazork at The Whispers Party at the Pyramid Club.

Nelson attends Joy Askew's performance at the Cat Club on January 14, 1986. He heads backstage briefly before Askew's set, then records the entire show. Before the video ends, he parties backstage for a bit.

unittitle.value: New Year's Eve at Pyramid with Love Delegation and Shazork #2

p.value: On disc one, Nelson is backstage at the Pyramid Club with friends as they wait for the performances on New Year's Eve. Nelson then heads to the dancefloor for a set by Peter Zaremba's Love Delegation with Wendy Wild and Liz Luv from Das Fürlines.

On disc two, Peter Zaremba's Love Delegation's performance continues. After the set, Nelson once again goes backstage. Throughout the video, a drag queen naps on a couch while everyone parties around her, but Nelson keeps returning to her. Shazork takes the stage and performs. The video ends with Nelson and the band backstage.

p.value: The Nelson Sullivan Video Collection is a collection of videorecordings made by video artist Nelson Sullivan (1948-1989). The collection consists of videotapes, film, photographic material and objects related to the city's art world and LGBT community as well as performances in clubs, house parties, and interactions with Sullivan's friends. The videos cover the period 1976-1989.
The collection is comprised of four series:
Series I: Videorecordings contains 8 boxes of videorecordings made by Nelson Sullivan.
Series III: Photographic Material contains 1 binder of slides covering the period between 1975 and 1977.

Copyright (or related rights to publicity and privacy) for materials in this collection was not transferred to New York University. Permission to use materials must be secured from the copyright holder. Please contact the Fales Library and Special Collections, fales.library@nyu.edu, 212-998-2596.
